# Fault source for the backend leg of property-fuzz. Every generated case that
# the driver routes to /mc exercises one occurrence of the memcached `get`
# command against this fake, and the fault stanzas below are keyed to those
# occurrences in order -- get:1 is the FIRST backend-routed generated case,
# get:2 the second, and so on. See backend-rst-midreply/backend and
# backend-lying-length/backend, which this mirrors.
#
# Sized generously (40 stanzas) for a checked-in seed that currently produces
# 11 backend-routed cases out of 40 iterations: the generator's branch
# (roughly one in four cases) is a property of the PRNG stream, not something
# this file can predict exactly, so there is headroom rather than an exact
# count. A fault whose occurrence number the run never reaches is inert --
# unused fault stanzas cost nothing -- so headroom is free and an exact count
# is not worth chasing (and would silently go stale the day the seed, the
# corpus size, or the branch probability changes).
#
# WHY 40, NOT 20 -- the REPLAY (driver.sh test 4) matters here. This fakesrv is
# a SINGLE process booted once by run-scenario.sh; its get:N counter runs over
# the whole process LIFETIME, and driver.sh runs the prober TWICE against it
# (test 3, then the test-4 replay). The second run therefore does NOT restart
# the counter -- it continues where the first left off (first run get:1..K,
# replay get:K+1..2K). With only 20 stanzas the replay's later backend cases
# would fall off the end onto NO fault stanza, i.e. hit a healthy backend and
# silently stop exercising ngx_http_upstream_finalize_request -- the exact
# teardown path this leg exists to cover. 40 stanzas guarantees BOTH runs stay
# inside a real fault for the current 11-per-run rate (22 total < 40) with the
# same headroom margin. NOTE this is verdict-level reproduction, not identical-
# fault-stream: the replay's backend cases traverse a DIFFERENT (phase-shifted)
# fault stanza than the first run, because the counter cannot be reset from the
# driver. Test 4 proves the leak/alive VERDICT reproduces (and still catches a
# case that flips pass->fail on replay); it does not claim the underlying fault
# stanza is byte-identical across the two runs.
#
# Four actions rotate across the occurrences, each a distinct upstream-failure
# shape that unwinds through ngx_http_upstream_finalize_request differently:
#   truncate      -- correct reply cut mid-frame, then RST (earliest possible
#                     upstream death: the client has parsed nothing usable)
#   rst           -- reset with nothing sent at all
#   accept_close  -- accepted then closed before a byte is read either way
#   lie_bytes     -- declared length disagrees with the payload (the classic
#                     reply-framing off-by-one, in both directions)
# None of these differ per key, so every seeded value is the same shape; what
# varies is how CORRECTLY it dies, not what it contains.
